MTS ORBITAL–DECAY DERIVATION 
────────────────────────────────────────────

1. Universal motion–curvature law
---------------------------------
α ∝ rⁿ
n = (1 − m) / 2

For a point-mass (Kepler) system:
m = 0  ⇒  n = +1/2

So:
α = k · r^(1/2)


2. Orbital energy relation
--------------------------
Total specific orbital energy:
E = −GM / (2r)

Then:
dE/dr = +GM / (2r²)


3. Rate of change of energy
---------------------------
If the orbital radius changes at rate ṙ:

Ė = (dE/dr) · ṙ
   = (GM / 2r²) · ṙ

From α ∝ r^(1/2):

(α̇ / α) = (1/2)(ṙ / r)
⇒ (ṙ / r) = 2(α̇ / α)

Substitute:

Ė = (GM / r) · (α̇ / α)


4. Curvature-tension bias Γκ
-----------------------------
Γκ is curvature persistence.

Its effect depends on the curvature regime (value of n):

• When n < 0   →  curvature is shallow  →  Γκ increases energy loss
• When n > 0   →  curvature is steep    →  Γκ reduces energy loss

For a point-mass binary (n = +1/2):
Γκ acts as a stabilising shield.

Thus:
Ė(MTS) = (1 − Γκ) · Ė(GR)


5. Relation to orbital period Pb
--------------------------------
Since:
E ∝ −1/r   and   r ∝ α²

We obtain:
Ė ∝ −α · α̇

Therefore:
(Ṗb / Pb) = − (α̇ / α)

Applying the MTS correction:

( Ṗb / Pb )_MTS = (1 − Γκ) · ( Ṗb / Pb )_GR

Hence:
Ṗb(MTS) = (1 − Γκ) · Ṗb(GR)


6. Observational fit: Hulse–Taylor Pulsar
------------------------------------------
Observed ratio:
Ṗ_obs / Ṗ_GR ≈ 0.997

Therefore:
1 − Γκ = 0.997
Γκ ≈ 3.0 × 10⁻³


7. Summary of physical meaning
------------------------------
• GR path:
  tensor field → wave equation → energy flux → orbital decay

• MTS path:
  α ∝ rⁿ → energy–radius link → Γκ correction → orbital decay

• In strong-field point-mass systems (n = +1/2) :
  Γκ > 0 reduces dissipation → slightly smaller |Ṗb|

• In cosmic weak-field systems (n ≈ −1/2) :
  Γκ > 0 increases dissipation → accelerating expansion without dark energy

